citeinfo.title: VBMP Digital Terrain Models - 2006/2007 (VA State Plane South)

descript.abstract:
The DTM (digital terrain model) files (broken down by USGS 1:24,000 quads - see companion grid file) were produced as part of the VGIN mapping project executed in 2006 and 2007 to support the creation of 4' contour files. Elevation datasets were provided to jurisdictions who chose to use the upgrade option for contour generation. This series represents the break lines of the DTM.
A companion layer is available to indicate where these obscured areas were.
These files contain Digital Elevation Model (DTM) file data for the County of Albemarle, Virignia developed from imagery acquired statewide in spring 2006 and 2007. In the spring of 2006, the Commonwealth of Virginia, through the Virginia Geographic Information Network Division (herein referred to as VGIN) of the Virginia Information Technologies Agency (VITA) contracted with the Sanborn Map Company to provide Aerial data acquisition, ground control, aerotriangulation and development of statewide DTM and digital orthophotography. Approximately 15% of the State was acquired in the year 2006 and the balance in 2007. All data acquired in 2006 is jurisdiction based. The data acquired in 2007 includes overlap along the boundaries of jurisdictions captured in the previous year 2006. This ensures each jurisdiction has full coverage from either Year 2006 or 2007, without 'mixing' imagery vintage along the edge of a jurisdiction. The project encompasses the entire land area of the Commonwealth of Virginia. The State boundary is buffered by 1000'. Coastal areas of the State bordering the Atlantic Ocean or the Chesapeake Bay shall be buffered by 1000' or the extent of man-made features extending from shore. The entire State was intially designed to support 1"=200' (1:2400) scale mapping. Jurisdictions throughout the State were provided an option to upgrade to a 1"=100' (1:1200) map scale. All data development processes for the DTM conform to the ASPRS Draft Aerial Photography Standards (1995) and Model Virginia Map Accuracy Standards (1992), which generally follow the ASPRS Accuracy Standard for Large-Scale Mapping (1990) for relevant mapping scales. The DTM supports the creation of 6-inch or 1-foot map orthoimagery at the relevant scales.
descript.purpose: The production of the DTM and aerial photography along with the subsequent othophotos was executed to capture the existing ground conditions at a specific point in time for the purpose of GIS analysis. DTM along with orthophotography typically provides an accurate base for digitally representing geographic features upon which a GIS is built. The Virginia Geographic Information Network (VGIN) is the lead public agency in the Commonwealth for spatial data and GIS. VGIN's mission is to facilitate the cost-effective development and use of spatial data, GIS, and related technologies in organizations throughout the Commonwealth.
descript.supplinf: The following jurisdictions were upgraded to 1"=100' mapping in year 2006: Alexandria, Bedford City, Bristol City, Charlottesville, Culpeper, Fredericksburg, Hampton, Harrisonburg, Lexington City, Norfolk, Norton City, Portsmouth, Purcellville, Prince William, Radford City, Roanoke, Salem City, Virginia Beach, Warren, Washington, Waynesboro, Wythe, portions of Stafford (Quantico area), portions of Orange County, portions of Cumberland, portions of Franklin. The following jurisdiction were upgraded to 1"=100' mapping in year 2007: Colonial Heights, Fairfax, Fairfax City, Falls Church, Franklin City, Galax, Isle of Wight, James City, Lynchburg, New Kent, Poquoson City, Pulaski, Richmond City, Spotysylvania, Williamsburg, portions of Clarke, portions of Dinwiddie, portions of Lancaster, and portions of Scott.

idinfo.useconst: This VBMP data has been developed using procedures designed to produce data to National Standard for Spatial Data Accuracy (NSSDA) and is intended for use at 1" = 100' or 1" = 200' scale. It is requested that the Commonwealth of Virginia be cited for any use of the orthophotography as follows: "Imagery Courtesy of the Commonwealth of Virginia".

dataqual.complete: The project consisted of a total of approximately 47,000 total DTMs in the Virginia North State Plane Zone for 1' = 200' and 1'=100' scale imagery.

procstep.procdesc: Digital Terrain Models were developed primarily for the purposes of orthorectification, except where jurisdictions chose to update to 2' or 4' contour data. The data was delivered in Microstation CAD .DGN format. The terrain is represented by masspoints and breaklines. Masspoints are stored on level 41; hydrologic breaklines are stored on Level 3, and all other breaklines on Level 2. For the areas mapped to 1"=200' mapping standards, the aerial imagery was collected at 1"=1,200' (1:14400) at a flying height of 7,200 feet above the mean terrain. For the areas mapped to 1"=100' mapping standards, the aerial imagery was collected at 1"=600' (1:7200) at a flying height of 3,600 feet above the mean terrain. 1"=200' map data was segmented into 5,000' X 5,000' tiles. The 1"=100' map data was segmented into 2,500 X 2,500' tiles. The original film negatives were scanned at 14 microns using high accuracy transparent film scanners. The Ground control used to support the orthophoto mapping was collected by either paneling of permanent monuments or photographic identification of strategic points. The coordinates were collected via ground survey techniques. Aerial Triangulation was performed on softcopy workstations using high accuracy stereo plotters and software with a fully analytical triangulation adjustment. The data was photogrammetrically stereo-compiled to North American Datum 1983; Virginia State Plane North or South Zone as applicable. All DTM was newly collected from the imagery acquired in 2006 or 2007, using high accuracy stereo plotters and traditional manual photogrammetric techniques for collection of the breaklines and masspoints. The bridges were coded uniquely and later removed from the final DTM file.
